Q: codeigniter routing functions A: <p>I think what you are trying to do is to have your <code>site</code> class as "default controller". Just try this : </p>

<pre><code>$route['default_controller'] = "site";
$route['(:any)'] = "site/view/$1";
$route['(:num)'] = "site/index/$1";
</code></pre>

<p>I don't really know what you are trying to do with your <code>site/view/$1</code> and <code>site/index/$1</code> it will work like this :</p>

<p><code>example.com/someaction</code> will match <code>$route['(:any)']</code> and will call the <code>view</code> method of the <code>site</code> controller with <code>someaction</code> as a string parameter. </p>

<p><code>example.com/2</code> will match <code>$route['(:num)']</code> and call the <code>index</code> action of the <code>site</code> controller with <code>2</code> as an integer parameter. </p>

<p><code>example.com/admin</code> will call the <code>index</code> action of the <code>admin</code> controller</p>

<p><code>example.com/admin/category</code> will call the <code>category</code> action of the <code>admin</code> controller</p>

Q: How to return the isolated result of a multiplication expression from a CodeIgniter query A: <p>Here is the most concise query builder script to return the isolated value from the multiplication expression. The select() method will not implement auto-quoting if a parenthesis is detected in the string.</p>
<pre class="lang-php prettyprint-override"><code>public function produk(): ?float
{
    return $this-&gt;db
        -&gt;select('(penjualan * jumlah) product')
        -&gt;get_where('toko', ['toko' =&gt; 'ALFA', 'produk' =&gt; 'susu'])
        -&gt;row('product');
}
</code></pre>
